<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the table-level WRITE ACL that
    grants the scoped role `x_casemgmt_case_agent` CONDITIONAL write access to
    `x_casemgmt_case` records inside the scoped application `x_casemgmt`. The
    condition restricts write to records where the calling user is the
    currently-assigned agent OR is a member of the currently-assigned group
    ("Assigned only" per AAP Section 0.5.6). This is the WRITE counterpart to
    the sibling READ ACL at ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_read_agent_assigned.xml; the
    advanced ACL script body is identical between the two records by design,
    since the same predicate gates both read and write access.

    AAP cross-references:
      - Section 0.5.6 (ACL Matrix) - case_agent row:
          | Role                  | Create | Read              | Write             | Delete |
          | x_casemgmt_case_agent  |  Yes   | Yes Assigned only | Yes Assigned only |  No    |
        This file authors the single "Write = Assigned only" cell. The "Yes"
        Create cell is authored by ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_create_agent.xml; the
        "Yes Assigned only" Read cell by ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_read_agent_assigned.xml;
        the "No" Delete cell is enforced by the deliberate ABSENCE of any
        x_casemgmt_case_delete_agent.xml file (ServiceNow record-level ACLs are
        deny-by-default: a role with no granting ACL for an operation cannot
        perform that operation).
      - Section 0.5.6 (ACL Matrix) - "Assigned only" definition:
          "Assigned only = cases where assigned_agent = current user OR
           assigned_group contains current user."
        The condition script below encodes this predicate exactly: it returns
        true if and only if (a) current.assigned_agent equals gs.getUserID(),
        OR (b) current.assigned_group is non-null AND the current user is a
        member of that group via the OOB sys_user_grmember join table
        (queried indirectly through gs.getUser().isMemberOf(groupSysId)).
        Default-deny: the script returns false if neither condition holds.
      - Section 0.7.3 (Validation Framework, Gate 3 - ACLs):
          "Role-based access enforced - case_viewer cannot write; case_agent
           cannot access unassigned cases; case_manager has full access."
        The middle clause ("case_agent cannot access unassigned cases") is
        the central correctness criterion of THIS file: this ACL must DENY
        write to a case where the agent is neither the assigned_agent nor a
        member of the assigned_group. The validation is exercised by the
        round-trip-verify procedure (../scripts/round_trip_verify.md) in
        which a demo case_agent attempts to write to seeded demo cases that
        are NOT assigned to them - the platform must reject the update with
        the OOB "Operation against this record is denied" message.
      - Section 0.4.3 (Design Pattern Applications - Scoped role-based
        access control): "Three named roles paired with table-level and
        field-level ACLs whose conditions are encoded as scripted ACL
        expressions, replacing ArkCase's ApplicationRolesToPrivilegesConfig
        map." This ACL is the table-level WRITE binding for the mid-tier
        scoped role and is one of the two records (alongside the READ
        sibling) where the "Assigned only" predicate is realized.
      - Section 0.1.2 (Technical Interpretation - Access-control
        transformation): "The 'Assigned only' condition for case_agent is
        encoded in the ACL condition script as a query: assigned_agent =
        current.sys_id OR assigned_group IN current.user_group_membership.
        No global ACLs are touched." The encoding is implemented below as
        a CDATA-wrapped scripted ACL expression on the table-level write
        operation.

    Why this is the WRITE counterpart to the READ ACL:
      Per AAP Section 0.5.6 the case_agent role is granted both Read and
      Write under the same "Assigned only" condition. It would be both
      operationally inconsistent and a usability anti-pattern to allow an
      agent to read a case but not update its description, status, or
      priority - case_agents are the daily operational drivers of the case
      lifecycle (Open -> In Progress -> Pending / Resolved per AAP
      Section 0.5.5). The two ACLs differ only in:
        - <operation>      "write" (this file)            vs "read"
        - <sys_id>         MD5("x_casemgmt_case.write...") vs MD5("x_casemgmt_case.read...")
        - <sys_update_name> *_write_agent_assigned        vs *_read_agent_assigned
      The CDATA script body is byte-identical between the two records by
      design; both encode the same predicate per AAP Section 0.5.6.

    How this ACL composes with field-level ACLs (defense in depth):
      This record grants TABLE-LEVEL write to case_agent for assigned cases.
      However the AAP Section 0.5.6 mandate ("ACLs MUST be defined at table
      level AND field level for sensitive fields") layers ADDITIONAL
      restrictions on top of this grant via two field-level ACLs:
        - ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_assigned_group_field_acl.xml: write
          restricted to x_casemgmt_case_manager only. A case_agent who has
          passed THIS table-level write check still cannot change the
          assigned_group field, because the field-level ACL applies on top
          of the table-level grant. In ServiceNow ACL evaluation, BOTH the
          table-level AND the field-level ACL must permit the operation
          for write to succeed.
        - ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_assigned_agent_field_acl.xml: write
          restricted to x_casemgmt_case_manager OR the currently-assigned
          case_agent (for self-handoff). A case_agent who has passed THIS
          table-level write check can change assigned_agent only if they
          themselves ARE the currently-assigned agent at write time.
      The net effect is the principle of least privilege: agents operate
      within their assigned cases (updating subject, description, status,
      priority, requester_*, opened_date, closed_date, etc.) but cannot
      reassign cases between groups (manager-only) and cannot poach
      assignments from other agents (only the current assignee or the
      manager may change assigned_agent). This same pattern is mirrored at
      the case_task and case_party levels by their respective siblings.

    Why <advanced>true</advanced> is REQUIRED (CRITICAL):
      The ServiceNow ACL evaluator only invokes the <script> body when
      <advanced> is true. With <advanced>false</advanced>, the platform
      evaluates only the <condition/> encoded query (which is empty here)
      and the <roles> field, granting write to ANY user holding
      x_casemgmt_case_agent regardless of assignment. This would directly
      violate AAP Section 0.5.6 and AAP Section 0.7.3 Gate 3 ("case_agent
      cannot access unassigned cases"). Setting advanced=true ensures the
      "Assigned only" predicate in the CDATA script body is actually
      evaluated for every write attempt.

    Semantic source-side reference (read-only context per AAP Section 0.3.2;
    no code or configuration is byte-for-byte ported from these files):
      - acm-services/acm-service-users/src/main/java/com/armedia/acm/services/
        users/model/ApplicationRolesToPrivilegesConfig.java
        ArkCase mapped roles to privileges through a single configuration map
        (`Map&lt;String, List&lt;Object&gt;&gt; rolesToPrivileges`) keyed by
        the property `application.rolesToPrivileges`. In that model, an
        "agent-equivalent" role would have been associated with privilege
        identifiers such as `acm-case-write` or `acm-case-update`, and the
        per-record "assigned only" check would have been imposed at runtime
        by Spring service classes (e.g., a SecurityFilter calling into
        AcmAssignedObject.getAssignee() and comparing against the
        authenticated principal). The ServiceNow target replaces this
        bifurcated model (declarative privilege list + imperative service
        check) with a single declarative scoped record-level ACL whose
        scripted condition body carries the identical predicate. This XML
        record is the direct equivalent of the (case_agent, WRITE,
        ASSIGNED-ONLY) cell in the conceptual ArkCase map.
      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-admin-plugin/src/main/java/com/
        armedia/acm/plugins/admin/service/RolesPrivilegesService.java
        Encapsulated role-CRUD and privilege-paging behavior in ArkCase
        (`retrieveRoles()`, `retrievePrivileges()`,
        `retrievePrivilegesByAuthorization(...)`,
        `retrievePrivilegesByRole(...)`, `updateRolePrivileges(...)`,
        plus a private role-name normalization step that uppercased the
        role, replaced whitespace with underscores, replaced periods with
        double-underscores, and prepended the constant `ROLE_` prefix
        from RolePrivilegesConstants). This entire service surface is
        replaced in the ServiceNow target by the platform's built-in
        sys_security_acl evaluator; no scripted privilege resolver is
        needed. The role-name-normalization step in particular is
        replaced by the scoped-application convention of using literal
        scope-prefixed role names (e.g., x_casemgmt_case_agent) directly
        in the <roles> field below - no `ROLE_` prefix is prepended, no
        case folding occurs, and the role name is treated as an opaque
        identifier resolved by name against the OOB sys_user_role table.

    Constraints honored (AAP Sections 0.7.1 and 0.7.2):
      - Scope-namespace exclusivity: every cross-reference resolves into
        the x_casemgmt scope (sys_scope = x_casemgmt, sys_package =
        x_casemgmt). No global-scope ACLs are written. The <name> field
        references the scoped table x_casemgmt_case (NOT the OOB `task`
        table or any other global table), and <roles> references the
        scoped role x_casemgmt_case_agent.
      - Zero hardcoded cross-reference sys_id literals: <name>, <roles>,
        <sys_scope>, and <sys_package> all resolve their targets by name /
        source attribute lookup at Update Set apply time. The CDATA
        script body uses gs.getUserID() (returns the runtime user's
        sys_id, NOT a literal) and current.assigned_agent /
        current.assigned_group field references (resolved by the
        platform at request time, NOT by literal). The <sys_id> below is
        THIS record's own deterministic primary key (MD5 of the canonical
        identifier "x_casemgmt_case.write.case_agent.assigned", a stable
        key for this exact ACL) and is not a cross-reference to any other
        record. Computing the sys_id deterministically guarantees the ACL
        is re-applyable / idempotent across fresh PDIs and round-trip
        Update Set previews per AAP Section 0.7.3 Gate 7.
      - Table-level (not field-level): <name> is `x_casemgmt_case` with NO
        dot. Field-level write restrictions on sensitive columns
        (assigned_group, assigned_agent) are authored separately in
        ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_assigned_group_field_acl.xml and
        ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_assigned_agent_field_acl.xml; those records
        compose with this one to produce the layered defense described
        above.
      - Operation = write: corresponds exactly to the "Write = Yes
        Assigned only" cell in the AAP matrix. The other operations
        (create, read, delete) are authored by separate ACL records.
      - admin_overrides = true: standard ServiceNow pattern that allows
        the platform `admin` role to bypass this ACL. This is required
        so platform administrators can troubleshoot, repair, or override
        scoped data without needing a case_agent role grant. It does NOT
        widen case_agent privileges - case_agents without admin still see
        exactly what this ACL permits.
      - active = true: ACL is in force the moment the Update Set commits.
      - advanced = true: the script body below IS evaluated at every write
        attempt (see "Why advanced=true is REQUIRED" rationale above).
      - condition (empty): no encoded-query condition is set; the entire
        access predicate lives in the scripted body. ServiceNow ACLs
        evaluate condition AND script (both must permit when both are
        present); leaving condition empty defers all logic to the script.

    Cross-dependencies and Update-Set ordering (AAP Section 0.5.2):
      MUST be loaded AFTER:
        - ../app/sys_app/x_casemgmt_case_management.xml (scoped app record)
        - ../app/sys_scope/x_casemgmt.xml (scope record - resolves
          sys_scope and sys_package source="x_casemgmt")
        - ../tables/x_casemgmt_case.xml (resolves <name>x_casemgmt_case</name>)
        - ../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_assigned_agent.xml (the script
          references current.assigned_agent; the column must exist when
          the script body is parsed/registered)
        - ../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_assigned_group.xml (the script
          references current.assigned_group; the column must exist when
          the script body is parsed/registered)
        - ../roles/sys_user_role_x_casemgmt_case_agent.xml (resolves
          <roles>x_casemgmt_case_agent</roles> by role name)
      MUST be loaded BEFORE:
        - ../seed-data/role_assignments/sys_user_has_role_x_casemgmt_demo_agent.xml
          (the demo agent's write access during round-trip verification
          depends on this ACL being applied first)
        - ../seed-data/cases/x_casemgmt_case_demo_*.xml (demo cases are
          inserted by the seed pass; this ACL governs subsequent demo-time
          writes by case_agent)

    The concrete scope identifier `casemgmt` is used verbatim per AAP convention. ServiceNow Update Set imports use a standard XML parser, so the
    scope id is concrete in the XML before export. The same identifier
    is used consistently across every artifact in this scoped application.
-->
<record_update table="sys_security_acl">
    <sys_security_acl action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">
        <active>true</active>
        <admin_overrides>true</admin_overrides>
        <advanced>true</advanced>
        <condition/>
        <description>Table-level ACL: x_casemgmt_case_agent can write x_casemgmt_case records ONLY when assigned_agent = current user OR assigned_group contains current user (per AAP Section 0.5.6 'Assigned only'). Field-level ACLs on assigned_group/assigned_agent further restrict those specific fields.</description>
        <name>x_casemgmt_case</name>
        <operation>write</operation>
        <roles>x_casemgmt_case_agent</roles>
        <script><![CDATA[(function() {
    var currentUserId = gs.getUserID();
    if (current.assigned_agent == currentUserId) {
        return true;
    }
    if (current.assigned_group && !current.assigned_group.nil()) {
        var groupId = current.assigned_group.toString();
        if (groupId && gs.getUser().isMemberOf(groupId)) {
            return true;
        }
    }
    return false;
})();]]></script>
        <sys_class_name>sys_security_acl</sys_class_name>
        <sys_created_by>admin</sys_created_by>
        <sys_created_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_created_on>
        <sys_id>44c5a728c4f234c957a8218eb121f643</sys_id>
        <sys_mod_count>0</sys_mod_count>
        <sys_name>x_casemgmt_case</sys_name>
        <sys_package display_value="Case Management" source="x_casemgmt">x_casemgmt</sys_package>
        <sys_policy/>
        <sys_scope display_value="Case Management">x_casemgmt</sys_scope>
        <sys_update_name>sys_security_acl_x_casemgmt_case_write_agent_assigned</sys_update_name>
        <sys_updated_by>admin</sys_updated_by>
        <sys_updated_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_updated_on>
        <type>record</type>
    </sys_security_acl>
</record_update>
